1 Introduction and motivation

General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a regulation that came into effect on 25 May 2018. GDPR aims to “protect fundamental rights and freedoms of natural persons and in particular their right to the protection of personal data” (Regulation, 2016). GDPR imposes obligations onto organisations anywhere, so long they target or collect data related to people in EU.

Since its establishment, Tikkinen-Piri, Rohunen, & Markkula (2018) stated that it would be a challenge to companies who lack awareness of the GDPR’s practical implications. In other words, inconsistent practical and technical implementation of GDPR across companies could be anticipated. By August 2020, more than 49 companies have been fined at least 100 thousand euros. Most of these fines were issued to IT companies (CoreView, 2020). The most famous and largest GDPR fine was the 50 million euros fine issued to Google.

Meanwhile, Lewis, Conleya, & Lee-Makiyama (2020) suggested that EU was in a bad position on the battle to its digital future. Besides, part of the reasons behind the GDPR establishment and the later digital services taxes imposed by major EU countries were an indication that EU was waving the flag of digital sovereignty. Thus, against digital hegemony, it intentionally targeted non-local held IT corporations.

Available data of GDPR fines from Privacy Affairs (2020), provides an opportunity for us to gain insight into the privacy issues and possible abuse of articles of GDPR in EU. This dataset was originally adopted by Tidy Tuesday (2020), which is a social weekly data project in R. github address here We outline the workflow of data collection, data cleaning and data analysis in the following sections.

2 Limitations

A potential limitation of this research is a great proportion of controller names(about 10%) are missing from the data set which introduces extra difficulties to draw accurate conclusions with respect to the company nationality and identity.

Fines documented by Privacy Affairs (2020) pertains to fines made public hence many of the fines may not be present. We might think of this data set as “high-profile” fines.

3 Data description

The data is scraped from Privacy Affairs (2020) by Ellis Hughes (2020), posted on Tidy Tuesday (2020). We adapted the scripts they used and removed duplication of GDPR fines due to multiple sources. We looked at data spanning from 2018-05-12 to 2020-08-21.

Abnormal values including fines with 0 price, indicating ongoing trails and fines before the establishment of the GDPR (which are missing values) are set NA. Records with missing date are also set to NA. We further process inconsistency in corporation names. There are a number of unnamed organizations fined by GDPR. in the data set. These are labelled as “Unknown”.

The dataset has some limitations that can be identified by the source Privacy Affairs (2020):
- Not all cases are presented in the dataset. The data only includes finalised cases and cases that are made public. This can lead to bias in further analysis. - The controller of data, in many cases, are vaguely described, or not disclosed. This may lead to misunderstanding and bias in our analysis.

The data consist of two datasets:

  1. GDPR_Violations.tsv contains information of 347 fines/penalties which data protection authorities (in EU) have imposed under GDPR. The dataset contains variables includes the country(where violation enforced) and authority, date of violation, fine price of violation in Euros.

  2. GDPR_text.tsv contains articles of GDPR (99 of them). Included are Chapter title, article number, artcile title and raw text of the article.

Each variable are detailed in next the Section (3.1).

variable class description

article_title character Article title
sub_article double Sub article number
gdpr_text character Raw text of article/subarticle
href character URL to the raw text itself

3.2 Research questions

The overall aim of this research is to examine the demographics in the application of the GDPR in practice since its implementation (in 25 May 2018) and unveil prevalent privacy issues in cyberspace in the EU.

Three secondary questions are addressed in this research:

  1. What were the characteristics of GDPR fines across countries, time and corporations? Did certain corporations being targeted by GDPR authorities?
  2. Which articles and regulations were more likely to be violated? And how much they commonly charged?
  3. What were the key words in each article, especially articles referenced the most in GDPR fines? Does this mean anything such as particular privacy issues?

3.3 Additional Questions

4 Analysis and findings

4.1 GDP violations across time since its implementation

Figure 4.1 shows the number of GDPR fines dished out in for each month for years 2018-2020. Time periods when high number of GDPR fines were recorded are highlighted red. The last quarter of 2019 and the first quarter of 2020 saw the highest number of GDPR violations, with a peak of 35 controllers fined in March 2020.

Figure 4.2 shows log price of GDPR fines against month for 2018-2020. We notice high price clustering (dots in red) between Sep 2019 and Apr 2020.
log price was used because price is an extremely skewed distribution. Using log scale of the price provide us with better data plot.

These outliers include Poland, Austria, Germany, Italy, Sweden and Netherlands. Looking at the spatial patterns of these outliers in Figure 4.3, we see countries are all closely connected to one other. We suspect there could be political reasons which could be worth the further study.

Table 4.1 shows us the information about the ten corporations that have accumulated the most fines since the introduction of GDPR. Notice only three of them are non-local corporations, which suggests we can not reject the hypothesis of multinational corporation is being fairly treated by GDPR.

Google was fined 2 times and had to pay a fortune of 57 million euros. It is worth notice that Vodafone España was fined 19 times, the highest number of financial penalties received. A closer look at the Britist telecommunication company is provided in table 4.2. We discovered another fact: Not only did Vodafone España receive a very high number of fines, its branch, Vodafone ONO also receive 2 fines. Together, Vodafone violated the GDPR 21 times in Spain, which is a fifth of the country’s total number of violations.

Overall, the last quarter of 2019 and the first quarter of 2020 saw the highest number of GDPR violations. Since the introduction of GDPR, most country has less than 30 violations, except for Spain. The country recorded about 100 GDPR financial penalties, 21 of which from Vodafone. It seems that Vodafone is targeted by the Spain authority.

Most of the violating companies; were large companies; especially with large amount of data.

4.2 Analysis of violated article

In this part, the researchers want to find out: Which articles and regulations were more likely to be violated? And how much they commonly charged?

Figure 4.7 answer the first question. Article 5 - “Principles relating to processing of personal data”, Article 6 - “Lawfulness of processing” and Article 32 - “Security of processing” are most likely to get violated by controllers. In fact, more than half of all violations are related to this three article. It indicates that the “Processing” of personal data in EU has issues, which lead to high number of violations. Further research could explore this issues and provide a more detail and clearer view.

Figure 4.7: Number of violations by GDPR articles

Figure 4.8 shows us violation of Article 5, 6 and 32 will lead to a relatively large fine, and with a high chance the amount of the fine will falls between 10000-100000 euros.

Figure 4.8: GDPR fines by article

4.3 Text mining GDPR articles

In this part, the researchers want to find out: What were the key words in each article, especially articles referenced the most in GDPR fines? How did it reflect the privacy issues in the EU?

4.3.1 Overview of words in GDPR articles

Figure 4.9 reflects the key concerns in GDPR. From the word cloud, we can see some regular words related to law such as “article”, “regulation”, “paragraph” and “pursuant”. We can also find words related to data governance, like “processing”, “processor”, “authority”, “supervisory” and “commission”. It seems like the GDPR provides a framework to govern the general data usage within EU and empower some authorities to supervise companies. More importantly, there are words explaining the spirit of GDPR, which are “freedom”, “personal”, “rights” and “public”. It tells us GDPR concerns about the personal and public freedom. Besides, we feel surprise that “privacy” is not a key words in GDPR.

Figure 4.9: Word cloud of GDPR

4.3.2 Words in Article 5, 6 and 32 respectively

In Table 4.3, there are words that repeatedly occurs. They are “data”, “process”, “personal” and “controller”. It suggests the most common privacy issue in EU is illegal processing of personal data. We can also find the most different words are “access” in Article 32, “subject” in Article 6 and “purposes” and “manner” in Article 5. It reflects slightly different core topics in these 3 articles. Other than that, they are very similar overall.

Trigram analysis can often provide us with more useful information about a text document. Figure 4.10 provides us with very special “GDPR” words. We can see “data protection officer”, which is probably the officer work for the authority, and “competent supervisory authority”, which is probably referring to the data protection authority.

Notice that there is a term “binding corporate rules”, this represents multinational corporations are allowed to transfer personal data in a intra-organizational manner. This rules increases the risk of potential leak of personal data on other nations outside EU.

Ignore these highly complicated article phrases, we can still find some interesting terms which we are familiar with. Like the one “historical research purpose”. It suggests data analysis is under consideration of GDPR.

Figure 4.10: Word cloud of trigram in GDPR

4.4 Major findings

In this part, the researchers highlight the major findings and identify areas for future research.

The reports finds that since the introduction of GDPR, the period from October, 2019 to April, 2020 saw the largest number of GDPR violations. Overall, most country has less than 30 violations, except for Spain. The country recorded about 100 GDPR financial penalties, 21 of which from Vodafone.

Regarding to the General Data Protection Regulation, the report discovers that the most commonly violated GDPR’s article are article 5, article 6 and article 32, All of which focused on the “Processing” of personal data. It indicates that the “Processing” of personal data in EU may have issues.

From this report, future research could consider focusing on the case of Spain and Vodafone Espana. The Britist telecommunication corporation received a fifth of the total financial penalties related to GDPR violations in Spain. Clearly, the Spain authorities have their eyes set on Vodafone.

Another research field that can be focusd on is the issues in the “Processing” of personal data in EU. As the most commonly violated GDPR’s article are all related to Processing of personal data, there seems to be issues in this field.

5 Conclusion

GDPR is one of the most widely touted regulation for personal data protection. From the characteristics of fines given out in countries in 4.1.1, there is a disparity in implementation - some countries catch the “big fishes” while some go for volumes. Most of the fines occur at the end the end of the year and first few months of a new year.

Besides, no such evidence supports that GDPR was generally used as an alternative to “digital service tax” against multinational corporations. However, one particular corporation, Vodafone, was targeted by the Spanish Data Protection Authority multiple times, which might be a special case. Moreover, the GDPR fines revealed that the most serious privacy issue in EU is the processing of personal data.
